LAYER 1 — Aesthetic Direction (WAJIB)
Before writing any code, commit to a bold aesthetic direction.
Choose ONE of these tones and execute it with full conviction:

- Brutalist/raw editorial
- Luxury/refined minimal
- Retro-futuristic
- Organic/natural
- Maximalist chaos
- Industrial/utilitarian
- Art deco/geometric

Whatever you choose, make it UNFORGETTABLE.
Ask yourself: "What's the ONE thing the user will remember about this UI?"

LAYER 2 — Typography Rules
Typography rules (STRICT):

- NEVER use Inter, Roboto, Arial, or system fonts
- Pick a DISTINCTIVE display font paired with a refined body font
- Use Google Fonts or variable fonts
- Typography should do visual heavy lifting
- Examples of good pairings: Playfair Display + DM Serif,
  Bebas Neue + Crimson Pro, Cabinet Grotesk + Lora

LAYER 3 — Color & Composition
Color & Layout rules:

- NO purple gradients on white. NO generic blue CTAs.
- Commit to a DOMINANT color with 1 sharp accent only
- Use CSS variables for full consistency
- Break the grid intentionally — asymmetry, overlapping elements,
  diagonal flow, generous OR dense (pick one, go all in)
- Backgrounds: use noise texture, gradient mesh, or layered
  transparency — NEVER flat solid white or #f8f8f8

LAYER 4 — Motion & Details
Motion & micro-interaction rules:

- ONE well-orchestrated page load with staggered reveals
  (animation-delay) beats scattered animations everywhere
- Hover states should SURPRISE the user
- Add: grain overlay, dramatic shadows, decorative borders,
  or custom cursor — pick what fits the aesthetic
- Every detail must serve the conceptual direction

LAYER 5 — The Anti-Generic Checklist (paste ini di akhir prompt)
Before finalizing, run this checklist:
[ ] Does it look like it could be from any random SaaS? → REDESIGN
[ ] Did you use Inter or Roboto? → CHANGE FONT
[ ] Is the background plain white or light gray? → ADD TEXTURE/CHARACTER  
[ ] Are all cards the same size in a symmetric grid? → BREAK THE LAYOUT
[ ] Does color feel "safe" and evenly distributed? → ADD DOMINANCE
[ ] Could this be mistaken for a Tailwind UI template? → START OVER

The goal: someone should be able to identify this brand
just from the visual language, without reading any text.
